                <note rend="inline" type="source">93.711/99: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to the
                        Minister in China (<persName type="to">Johnson</persName>)</hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1933-03-09T12:00:00-05:00"
                            >March 9, 1933—noon</date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>79. Your 220, March 7, 3 p.m. Your view as expressed in the last paragraph of
                    your telegram under reference is in substantial <pb facs="0787" n="685"
                        xml:id="pg_685"/> accord with the Department’s view as expressed in the last
                    paragraph of the Department’s 373, November 21, 1932, 5 p.m.<note n="79"
                        xml:id="d749fn79">
                        <ref target="frus1932v04#pg_665">
                            <hi rend="italic">Foreign Relations</hi>, 1932, vol. <hi
                                rend="smallcaps">iv</hi>, p. 665</ref>.</note>
                </p>
                <p>You are therefore authorized to act accordingly but, in view of the fact that you
                    have discussed this question with your British colleague, the Department feels
                    that you should again, before taking action, discuss the matter with him in the
                    light of recent developments; also, with any other of your interested colleagues
                    with whom you may have discussed the matter.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Hull</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
